[SN]TITLE[SN]
Bosses of Dundee KFC restaurant charged over beetles

[SN]FIRST-SENTENCE[SN]
The bosses of a Dundee KFC restaurant are to face charges in court after live beetles and flies were allegedly found in the kitchen and serving areas.

[SN]RESTBODY[SN]
Operators of the franchise on the High Street have been charged under food safety and hygiene regulations after an inspection in September last year.
Scotco Eastern Ltd, based in Aberdeen, has made no plea or declaration.
The case at Dundee Sheriff Court was continued until July after a request from the fiscal depute.
The charges, brought under the Food Safety Regulations of 1995 and the Food Hygiene (Scotland) Regulations 2006, allege that live house flies were found on the front serving counter and in food preparation areas, while live beetle larvae is said to have been found on the floor under the front counter.
Beetles are larvae were also allegedly found in the office, under a coffee machine and on the floor under a dessert preparation area.
